        "text":  "९ कुत्स आङ्गिरसः। ऋभवः। जगती, ५, ९ त्रिष्टुप्।\n\n        त॒तं मे॒ अप॒स्तदु॑ तायते॒ पुन॒: स्वादि॑ष्ठा धी॒तिरु॒चथा॑य शस्यते ।\n\n        अ॒यं स॑मु॒द्र इ॒ह वि॒श्वदे॑व्य॒: स्वाहा॑कृतस्य॒ समु॑ तृप्णुत ऋभवः ॥१॥\n\n        आ॒भो॒गयं॒ प्र यदि॒च्छन्त॒ ऐत॒नापा॑का॒: प्राञ्चो॒ मम॒ के चि॑दा॒पय॑: ।\n\n        सौध॑न्वनासश्चरि॒तस्य॑ भू॒मनाग॑च्छत सवि॒तुर्दा॒शुषो॑ गृ॒हम् ॥२॥\n\n        तत् स॑वि॒ता वो॑ऽमृत॒त्वमासु॑व॒दगो॑ह्यं॒ यच्छ्र॒वय॑न्त॒ ऐत॑न ।\n\n        त्यं चि॑च्चम॒समसु॑रस्य॒ भक्ष॑ण॒मेकं॒ सन्त॑मकृणुता॒ चतु॑र्वयम् ॥३॥\n\n        वि॒ष्ट्वी शमी॑ तरणि॒त्वेन॑ वा॒घतो॒ मर्ता॑स॒: सन्तो॑ अमृत॒त्वमा॑नशुः ।\n\n        सौ॒ध॒न्व॒ना ऋ॒भव॒: सूर॑चक्षसः संवत्स॒रे सम॑पृच्यन्त धी॒तिभि॑: ॥४॥\n\n        क्षेत्र॑मिव॒ वि म॑मु॒स्तेज॑नेनँ॒ एकं॒ पात्र॑मृ॒भवो॒ जेह॑मानम् ।\n\n        उप॑स्तुता उप॒मं नाध॑माना॒ अम॑र्त्येषु॒ श्रव॑ इ॒च्छमा॑नाः ॥५॥\n\n        आ म॑नी॒षाम॒न्तरि॑क्षस्य॒ नृभ्य॑: स्रु॒चेव॑ घृ॒तं जु॑हवाम वि॒द्मना॑ ।\n\n        त॒र॒णि॒त्वा ये पि॒तुर॑स्य सश्चि॒र ऋ॒भवो॒ वाज॑मरुहन् दि॒वो रज॑: ॥६॥\n\n        ऋ॒भुर्न॒ इन्द्र॒: शव॑सा॒ नवी॑यानृ॒भुर्वाजे॑भि॒र्वसु॑भि॒र्वसु॑र्द॒दिः ।\n\n        यु॒ष्माकं॑ देवा॒ अव॒साह॑नि प्रि॒ये॒ ३ ऽभि ति॑ष्ठेम पृत्सु॒तीरसु॑न्वताम् ॥७॥\n\n        निश्चर्म॑ण ऋभवो॒ गाम॑पिंशत॒ सं व॒त्सेना॑सृजता मा॒तरं॒ पुन॑: ।\n\n        सौध॑न्वनासः स्वप॒स्यया॑ नरो॒ जिव्री॒ युवा॑ना पि॒तरा॑कृणोतन ॥८॥\n\n        वाजे॑भिर्नो॒ वाज॑सातावविड्ढ्यृभु॒माँ इ॑न्द्र चि॒त्रमा द॑र्षि॒ राध॑: ।\n\n        तन्नो॑ मि॒त्रो वरु॑णो मामहन्ता॒मदि॑ति॒: सिन्धु॑: पृथि॒वी उ॒त द्यौः ॥९॥",
        "translation":  "THE holy work I wrought before is wrought again: my sweetest hymn is sung to celebrate your praise.\nHere, O ye á¹šbhus, is this sea for all the Devas: sate you with Soma offered with the hallowing word.\nWhen, seeking your enjoyment onward from afar, ye, certain of my kinsmen, wandered on your way, Sons of Sudhanvan, after your long journeying, ye came unto the home of liberal Indra.\nIndra therefore gave you immortality, because ye came proclaiming him whom naught can hide; And this the drinking-chalice of the Devas, which till that time was one, ye made to be fourfold.\nWhen they had served with zeal at offering as monks, they, mortal as they were, gained immortality. The á¹šbhus, children of Sudhanvan, bright as suns, were in a year\u0027s course made associate with prayers.\nThe á¹šbhus, with a rod measured, as â€™twere a field, the single sacrificial chalice. wide of mouth, Lauded of all who saw, praying for what is best, desiring glorious fame among Immortal Devas.\nAs oil in ladles, we through knowledge will present unto the Heroes of the Firmament our hymn. The á¹šbhus who came near with this great Father\u0027s speed, and rose to Heaven\u0027s high sphere to eat the strengthening food.\ná¹šbhu to us is Indra freshest in his might, á¹šbhu with powers and wealth is giver of rich gifts. Devas, through your favou. May we on the happy day quell the attacks of those who pour no offerings forth.\nOut of a skin, O á¹šbhus, once ye formed a cow, and brought the mother close unto her calf again. Sons of Sudhanvan. Heroes, with surpassing skill ye made your aged Parents youthful as before.\nHelp us with strength where spoil is won, O Indra: joined with the á¹šbhus give us varied bounty. This prayer of our. May Indra grant, and Mitra, and Aditi and Sindhu, Earth and Heaven."
