        "translation":  "A THOUSAND are thy helps for us, O Indra: a thousand, Lord of Bays, thy choice refreshments.\nWealth of a thousand sorts hast thou to cheer us. May precious goods come nigh to us in thousands.\nMay the most sapient Devas, with protection, with best boons brought from lofty Heaven, approach . Now when their team of the most noble horses speeds even on the sea\u0027s extremest limit.\nClose to them clings one moving in seclusion, like a man\u0027s wife, like a spear carried rearward, well grasped, bright, decked with gold there is VÄk also, like to a courtly, eloquent dame, among them.\nFar off the brilliant, never-weary Devas cling to the young Maid as a joint possession. The Devas wished for her to grow their friend and fellow.\nShe climbed her servant\u0027s chariot, she like SÅ«rya with cloud-like motion and refulgent aspect.\nUpon their car the young men set the Maiden wedded to glory, mighty in assemblies, when your song, Devas, rose, and, with oblation, the Soma-pourer sang his hymn in worship.\nI will declare the greatness of these Devas, their real greatness, worthy to be lauded. How, with them, she though firm, strong-minded, haughty, travels to women happy in their fortune.\nIndra guards from censure. Firm things are overthrown that neâ€™er were shaken: he prospers, Devas, who gives choice oblations.\nNone of us, Devas, near or at a distance, hath ever reached the limit of your vigour. They in courageous might still waxing boldly have compassed round their foemen like an ocean.\nMay we this day be dearest friends of Indra, and let us call on him in fight to-morrow. So were we erst. New might attend us daily! So be with us! á¹šbhuká¹£an of the Heroes!\nMay this your laud, may this your song, O Devas, sung by the poet, MÄna\u0027s son, MÄndÄrya, Bring offspring for ourselves with. food to feed us. May we find strengthening food in full abundance."
